review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a dark chocolate-garnet color with tight off-white head. Poor retention and no lacing. Aroma is of maple and nuts. Front palate is of caramel with a nutty-malty middle and slightly bitter finish. Medium body, low carbonation.

12 oz. bottle pours a golden honey color with frothy head. Poor retention, but abundant lacing. Aroma is of pine resin, moss and crackers. Front palate is bitter and malty with a middle of herbs and grass and a hoppy finish with yeast overtones and a burnt-popcorn aftertaste.  A crisp fall accompaniment for a warm spinach salad with bacon, bleu cheese and a homemade honey mustard dressing.

12 oz. bottle pours a hazy ruby-pumpkin color with soft, lazy head. Moderate retention, minimal lacing. Aroma is initially of burnt tires/brakes, softening into floral tones. Flavor is more complex than expected with front palate of grain, middle of herbs and finish of grapefruit. Aftertaste is of hops. Nice fall accompaniment for roasted squash, eggplant and asparagus risotto.

12 oz. bottle pours an unnatural butter-yellow color with dense, pillowy head. Moderate retention, no lacing. Aroma is of grass and hay with malt. Weak palate with middle of malt and a bitter, skunky, almost sour finish. The wheat-like aftertaste is the most pleasant feature.

12 oz. bottle pours a dark, opaque brownish-black with garnet highlights and a creamy, tan head. Aroma is of nuts and dark chocolate. Front palate is nutty and earthy with malt in the middle and a finish of dried fruit: raisins, dates, plums. Aftertaste is of the chocolate variety. Smooth brown ale. Another reason I love Brooklyn beers. Would be nicely paired with an herb-crusted buffalo roast or steak with roasted veggies and potatoes.

beer_brewer_name: Old Dominion Brewing Company (Coastal Brewing Co.)
review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a golden copper with a tangerine halo. No head to speak of. Aroma is of caramel and malt. Nutty front palate with caramelized sugar middle and finish of very slight sweet hay. No discernable hoppiness. Easy to drink and easy to get a hold of, but not exciting or interesting at all.

12 oz. bottle pours a sunshine-y yellow with pillowy head. Aroma is of sweet malt, lemon and wheat. Front palate is of sweet cereal with a middle of a new plastic blow-up toy (like a beach ball - not unpleasant, but I dont know that that flavor IS). Finish is of a crisp lime-hoppiness. Light body with a fresh taste overall. Very fresh-tasting summertime brew.

12 oz. bottle pours a clear ruby-amber with tightly packed head that leaves sparse lacing. Aroma is strong of pine right out of the bottle, but eases into florals and popcorn as it airs. Front palate is of sweet hay with spices - nutmeg? middle is doughy with a warm maltiness and a smooth finish of citrus with a hot, hoppy aftertaste. Not too bitter and definitely easy to drink. With a nice smooth finish, this could easily be a nice session if the ABV were lower. Nicely paired with Caribbean beef and chicken kabobs on the grill.

12 oz. can pours a clear ruddy orange with frothy head. Aroma is of malt and apricots. Front palate is of more apricots with a malty middle and spicy finish. Aftertaste is reminiscent of cloves. A little heavier in body than I anticipated and I dont taste any of the ginger touted in the deScription. That said, its certainly not the worst beer Ive ever had and the name and picture on the can are definitely worth a good chuckle. An "OK" beer to beat the heat.

12 oz can pours a marigold yellow with a fine haze of head which leaves a thick lacing. Aroma is grassy and crisp with a follow up of sweet hay. Palate is simple - not complex. Little distinction in the front palate, with a strong middle of hops and a blossom-y finish. Follow up is a hoppy aftertaste. Not bad, middle-of-the-road beer that is drinkable with fun art on the can, but not necessarily one of the best of its style. Not the worst either though.
beer_name: Central City Red Racer Pale Ale

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a golden yellow with large, frothy head. Moderate carbonation. Malty, bread-like aroma with a fresh-grain sweetness. Not a lot of distinguish-ability in the palates for me. A lot of consistent maltiness, mellow oats and grasses with a smooth finish and little to no aftertaste. Not especially complex, but easily drinkable and a nice smooth beer for a 104 degree day in the DC swampland.

Bottle pours a hazy sunshine yellow with abundant pillowy white head. Appearance is of heavy carbonation but this dissipates as the beer airs and doesnt come through in the texture or taste. Front palate is of lemon and sweet blossoms with a full malty middle and slight hop finish. I actually prefer this to many of the beers touted as a "Summer Ale." Its definitely more malty than a hefe, and this might make it too heavy for some, but I find it (too) easy to drink and much smoother than I had anticipated. This may be the most appealing Samuel Adams Ive ever had.

On tap at Chadwicks in Old Town Alexandria, VA. Clear golden color with no head (by the time the server got it to our table). Soft floral aroma followed by warm malty bready-ness. Front palate of mild hops with abundant malt in the middle and mild floral in the finish - like an orange blossom. Very smooth. The kind of beer you could sit around and drink pint after pint of on a hot, humid VA afternoon, and not too bad with a Cobb Salad, either.

12 oz. bottle pours a honey color with pillowy white head. Aroma is initially of juniper and hops but mellows into bready malt. Front palate is citrus-fruity with a strong middle of malt and pine followed up by a strong hoppy finish. Tasty EIPA that is well-balanced and mellows into a really drinkable beer.

12 oz. bottle pours clear goldenrod yellow with fuzzy head which leaves healthy lacing. Appearance of high carbonation as it sits. Aroma of grass and oats with lemon oil. Palate is simple with sweet malt and blossoms followed by mild hoppiness. Mediocre offering from Redhook, but easy to drink and could be a nice, easy segue to micros. Easy to down a few with early summer grill fare.
On tap at brewpub in Granby, CT. Pours a caramel color with minimal off-white head. Aroma of malt and sugar. Front palate of caramel and toffee with a creamy middle and smooth finish.
beer_name: The Cambridge House Old Mill Pond ESB

review_blob: On tap at brewpub in Granby, CT. Pours a light orange-copper color with a sweet fruity aroma. Balanced blend of hops and malt. Smooth finish with minimal aftertaste.
beer_name: The Cambridge House Abijah Rowe IPA

review_blob: On tap at brewpub in Granby, CT. Pours a cloudy sunshine yellow with sparse head. Aroma of apricots. Front palate of bread with a malty middle amd light lemony finish. Hoppy aftertaste.
beer_name: The Cambridge House Picozzis Fat Ass Ale (2007-)

review_blob: On tap at the brew pub in Granby, CT. Aroma of citrus and hops with a hint of banana. Front palate of orange with hoppy backbone and a bitter finish. Funky aftertaste that definitely depreciates the experience.
beer_name: The Cambridge House Copper Hill Kolsch

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a fetching garnet-ruby red with thick, milky head. Sparse lacing. Moderate carbonation with an aroma far stronger of hops than I had expected but with overtones of toffee and malt to mellow it out. Front palate is of roasted grains with a malty, caramel middle and hoppy twinge with citrus notes at the end. A pleasantly surprising (and surprisingly pleasant) beer.

12 oz. bottle pours a foggy gold with frothy head which leaves small islands but no lacing as it melts. Aroma is of...well...bellybutton lint is the closest thing Ive ever smelled (I wouldnt admit that if I hadnt been drinking). Overall taste is overwhelmingly of ginger. Front palate is slightly floral and lemony, with that ginger in the middle and a yeasty finish. Aftertaste is like gingerale. This is not entirely unpleasant, but definitely one of the more bizarre beers Ive ever tasted. Almost interesting if only for the unusual composition. I might give it another go if I could pair it with sushi and a good chunk of wasabi.

12 oz. bottle pours an unnatural mauve color, like if you poured a touch of Chambord liquor in a beer. Pillowy, poufy head quickly dissipates, leaving abundant lacing and scant islands in the beers surface. Aroma is of a stale, overprocessed pop tart. Fake, fruity overtones with a starchy, processed grain base. The flavor reminds me of something about childhood. I think its either the flavor of the kiddie cosmetics I used to play with, or maybe the paint my dad used on the Barbie case he made for me. Front palate is overpowered by the smell, so I really didnt get much taste. Mid palate is of Corona with lime and rancid Chambord with a finish of Sour Patch Kids. I feel that with fruit/veg beers, either theyre great or really bad - not very many that are just okay. This is neither great nor okay. The remainder was a drain pour.

12 oz. can pours a sunny golden color with tight head and abundant carbonation. Aroma is of sweet green hay and oats. Kind of reminiscent of a stable. Front palate is dry and crisp with a warmer, malty middle and oddly vanilla-sugar sweetness at the finish. Slightly strange aftertaste like cotton candy without the overwhelming sweetness. Not the worst beer Ive ever had, and possibly a good entry-level beer for the hesitant micro tryer.

12 oz. bottle pours an intruiging copper-orange with a pinkish hue. Large head leaves sparse lacing. Aroma is hoppy with sweet, floral overtones. Hoppy front palate with solid malty middle and crisp citrus finish. Hints of bubblegum and corriander carry consistently throughout. 
This is not what I expected given the Belgian-style IPA deScription on the label. The unexpected mix of hoppiness of an IPA with the softer, floral spiciness of a Belgian was a very pleasant surprise. This may become a go-to beer for many months as it is a great way to welcome the warmer days of spring as they ease into the hotter days of summer. Could be a lovely accompaniment to a mild caesar salad, a beautiful mid-rare buffalo roast cooked over an oak chipped BBQ grill, garlic roasted potatoes and fresh green beans straight from the garden.

12 oz. bottle pours a golden amber with tight white head. No lacing. Aroma of nutmeg, bubblegum and Coors. Unexpected and a little weird. Front palate of malt and yeast with a floral middle and mild hoppy finish. Maybe not a wonderful beer IMO, but definitely drinkable and light enough for a session beer. It reminds me more of a fall-time beer than one intended for spring, and makes me think it would be good in a gigantic beer stein at an Oktoberfest celebration.

12 oz. bottle pours a pleasant dark chocolate brown color with a foamy tan head. Aroma is overwhelmingly of coffee - almost like old coffee grounds. Body is thin to medium and the taste is also overwhelmingly of coffee and dirt. A hint of what could be toast - if it were burnt - but I was unable to taste any of the maltiness or mellow roast that I love in so many stouts. Although it could easily be my uneducated palate, this is the first Bells beer that has disappointed, and not one Ill try again anytime soon.

12 oz. bottle pours a thick, opaque black with about 1/2" of cocoa-colored, frothy head. Aroma is nutty with a waft of sweet roastiness.  The body is moderate with an oat flavor in the front palate, a malty, milky middle and a roasty grain finish. Easy to drink  but not too filling.

12 oz. bottle pours a dirty peach with off white head. Initially, the aroma of hops pushes out of the pour, followed by a gentle wafting of caramel. Medium bodied with solid but not overwhelming carbonation. Flavors of crisp leafy florals in the front palate, warming to a citrus malt in the middle with a finish of earthy woods and hops. Slight citrus aftertaste. Enjoyable and versatile, this might become one of my go-to session beers as its a little lighter for me than SNPA.

650 ml. bottle pours black as night with a cocoa colored poufy head that leaves striations of lacing as it melts. Aroma initially is of candied black licorice warming to a bitter dark chocolate. Front palate is malty with a barley taste in the middle and a bitter finish that s not hoppy, but more like a bitter bark taste. I think this is how this beer is supposed to taste, but Im wondering if this style is not for me, or if the high ABV has to do with my inability to bond with it.

12 oz. bottle pours a rich amber with two fingers of pillowy, off-white head which leaves sporadic lacing as it dissipates. Aroma is of caramel and toffee with notes of pine. Light bodied ale with an earthy front palate, a middle palate of grains and hops and a heavy hoppy finish and aftertaste. A nice winter ale with flavors strong enough to stand up to winters heavier dishes (scalloped potatoes and roast beef with fresh horseradish and asparagus) yet not overwhelmingly strong.
beer_name: Southern Tier Old Man Winter Ale

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a ruby-amber color with little head. Moderate carbonation and light to medium mouth feel follow an aroma of caramel and pepperoni. Taste is of burnt marshmallows with a slight finish of nutmeg and cinnamon. Easy to drink but weird as hell. Kind of like being in the Fun House of beers, only just kind of weird instead of fun.

11.2 oz (330ml) bottle pours an opaque amber-ochre color. Aroma is of corriander, raisins and dates with a thick malty backbone. Medium mouthfeel, not overly carbonated. Flavors of cereal, figs and raisins with an earthy, dough-like finish and a sweet aftertaste. Not a session beer for me, but nice for a  cold winter night inside. Nicely paired with a smoked applewood bacon pork loin and homemade mac n cheese.

12 oz. bottle pours a deep mahogany red with frothy head that left sparse lacing. Aroma was sweet like molasses and candied cherries mixed with roasted nuttniness. Front palate is malty with a bitter cocoa middle and finish of nuts with a hint of dried fruit. Smooth and easy to drink with a medium body. This seems like a quality beer that has session potential, albeit maybe a short session, given the ABV.

beer_brewer_name: Leinenkugel Brewing Company (Tenth & Blake Beer Co.)
review_blob: 12 oz. bottle. Aroma is VERY faint. A little sweetness, some caramel maybe and some roasted nut. Appearance is a dark reddish-amber with virtually no head to speak of that disappears the second it hits the glass.  Taste is mostly smoky, like a smoked almond. But a smoked almond thats not really smoked but has that weird smoked powder flavoring shaken onto it. Malty maple in the middle and that overwhelmingly bizarre smokey flavor at the end again. Leinenkugel isnt my favorite line by any stretch, but this beer seems to be even less so than others. Not undrinkable, but...why? Theres really no reason. Id almost rather have a Bud Light. At least that tastes like something, even if it is corn.

12 oz. bottle (batch #9422) pours an orange-amber with mucho gordo off-white head that leaves rings of lacing when it dissipates. Aroma is of malt and caramel with a light waft of hops. Medium body with light carbonation. Hoppy front palate with pine-y middle and soft wheat and barley finish. A nice, mellow winter ale that has the crispness reminiscent of light hops, but whose predominant characteristic is malt.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours opaque black - just like my soul - but this beer has a limited amount of poufy head that dissipates quickly, leaving moderate lacing as it goes. Aroma is initially of wet dog, which is offputting to say the least, but then warms up to a nice caramel and coffee aroma. Low carbonation with a light to medium mouthfeel. Malty goodness throughout with a smoky finish and coffee aftertaste.

22 oz. bottle pours a cloudy orange-ish color with a moderate amount of fine, wispy head. Aroma is heavy and sweet, of candied fruit, honey and bread. Low carbonation but sickly sweet with a strong flavor of clove. Now I remember why I got so sick when I smoked those clove cigarettes in junior high school.
beer_name: Heavy Seas Mutiny Fleet Yule Tide (- 2012)

review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a ruby-amber with creamy off-white head. Aroma is initially malty with honey then warms into gingerbread-type spices. Front palate is roasty caramel with a heartier, spicy middle. The rear palate pushes forward with a strong hoppy showing and a grassy aftertaste.

beer_brewer_name: Old Dominion Brewing Company (Coastal Brewing Co.)
review_blob: 12 oz. bottle pours a vitamin-induced orange urine color with a thin, dilute head that instantly disappears.  Aroma is of corn and hay. Thin mouthfeel with mild toasted malt flavors. Overly carbonated with a mid palate of grass and a bitter hoppy  finish. Some pine-y aftertaste.

12 oz. bottle pours a copper color with foamy white head. Aroma is of malt with piney underpinnings. Front palate is dry and of green hay with warm middle of pine, spice and yeast and a hearty hops finish. Mild aftertaste of hops. Nicely blended beer with a solid profile of malt and hops without being too over the top hoppy. Would pair nicely with crisp greens or a lightly flavored chicken dish.

12 oz. bottle pours a rich amber with a golden haze and sparse head that melts quickly. Aroma is floral with earthy undertones and light waft of pumpkin/vegetable. Front palate is malty with pumpkin and gentle allspice middle. Finish is lightly laced with cinnamon. Medium to light body. Flavors blend nicely but theres not as much complexity as Id like. That said, its one of the better pumpkin beers Ive had, and it actually has some pumpkin flavor. This beer is too light to pair with a lot of the heartier fall fare, but would be a nice addition for a wilted spinach salad with roasted turkey, cranberries and candied walnuts.

22 oz. bottle pours cloudy amber with tight white head that leaves minimal runny lacing as it fades. Aroma is heavy with spice, not much pumpkin. Allspice, and cinnamon are prevalent. Moderately thin to medium body with a malty front, nutmeg and cinnamon middle and clove finish with an overall mild pumpkin-squash palate. The alcohol is not well hidden in the aftertaste. This is a heartier fall/pumpkin ale, but very little pumpkin comes through for me. As with many of the fall seasonals, this beer tends to display spicier notes than pumpkin, lending itself to better be called (IMO) a fall, or spice ale, rather than pumpkin. That said, this is a nice accompaniment to a sun-dried tomato marinated turkey breast stuffed with spinach, sugared walnuts and goat cheese.
beer_name: Heavy Seas Mutiny Fleet The Great Pumpkin

review_blob: UPDATED: OCT 18, 2010

12 oz. bottle poured a coppery color with frail, dense, off-white head which left no lacing as it melted. Stable, creamy aroma of pumpkin, allspice and nutmeg. Thin body. Flavor of pumpkin, malt and cinnamon with a clove finish and aftertaste of alcohol. I liked this beer more than I had anticipated. It is one of the few pumpkin ales in which I can actually taste pumpkin in addition to the spices. However, I dont feel that the alcohol was masked effectively and I was hoping for a richer, thicker, more "brown ale" feel overall instead of the watery "macro-micro" feel. I still feel that, as with most of the DFH beers, this one is over-priced and over-hyped. I will say though, in all fairness, that DFH onion rings are the bomb!

12 oz. bottle pours a clear ruby-amber color with a generous furry off white head. Aroma is overwhelmingly of nutmeg just out of the gate, but warms to some allspice and pumpkin. Front palate of sweet malt with a gingery middle and nutmeg finish. Aftertaste of  clove. Thin, watery, "ale"-ish only in color. Not too carbonated. Interesting attempt but unimpressive.

12 oz. bottle pours a watery copper color with dense, large head that leaves intricate lacing as it dissipates. Aroma is of wet, green hay. Flavor is like sucking on a stalk of wheat in August. I bought this beer because of the cool and interesting label, and now see that thats the best thing about it.   It does have a cool label though.

12 oz. bottle, bottled Winter 07-08, pours a thick black tar color with a finger of frothy, tan-mocha colored head that leaves a delicate, sparse lacing. Aroma is of a vanilla malt, rich with roasted cocoa bean undertones. Front palate is of alcohol, but not nearly as much as Id anticipated given the ABV. This melts into a creamy middle of milk chocolate and a bittersweet finish. The palate is very complex - too complex for me to pick out a lot of specifics - but delicious nonetheless. By far, this is my favorite higher ABV beer. Nice medium body, flavorful yet not too overwhelming. Id love to make this into a vanilla-bean float or serve it with a caramel chocolate lava cake ala mode. Much better quality (IMO) than the Shenandoah Chocolate Donut beer (my previous chocolate fave).

12 oz. bottle pours a light buttery amber color with huge tight off white head. Aroma is of wet grass and hay. Some malt up front with a roasted, earthy middle and leathery finish with a mild hops aftertaste. Thin body, overly carbonated and would have significant difficulty standing up to pairing with the seasons heartier dishes.

12 oz. bottle pours a ruby-copper color with carbonation swirlies throughout, culminating in frothy off-white head. Aroma is of malty maple. Front palate is caramel with a wheaty, hay-like  middle and finish thats almost sour.  Thin bodied. Not as hearty as Id hoped.

12 oz. bottle pours cloudy cinnamon color with frothy off white head that leaves little lacing. Aroma is strong of fermenting apples and caramel with underpinnings of yeast. Front palate is malty with a nutty middle and a tin-like finish. Not one of my favorite Left Hand brews.
